<TextContainer Title="Philosophy">
    <p>
        As a speech-language pathologist who adheres to the life-participation approach, my goal is to provide interventions in a way that leads to functional results and reduces handicap situations caused by communication difficulties.
    </p>

    <p>
        My approach is designed to help you resume or improve your communication activities, whatever they may be. Whether you want to hold a conversation, listen to a news report, read an article, write an e-mail, speak up... the intervention plan we will build starts from your projects, your goals!
    </p>

    <p>
   I consider communication in its social context and base interventions on the theoretical frameworks of neuroscience and learning psychology. I work in collaboration with the person living with the communication disorder and his or her support system whenever possible and desirable.
    </p>

    <p>
        I offer individual or dyadic therapies (see conditions below). I am also an active speech-language pathologist with the .<a href="https://aphasie.ca/" target="_blank">Association Québecoise des Personnes Aphasiques (AQPA)</a> through the <a href="https://aphasie.ca/projet-sappa/" target="_blank">Service aux proches d'une Personnes Aphasique (SAPPA)</a> program offering dyad interventions and support groups for people living with post-stroke aphasia and their families, as well as for people living with primary progressive aphasia and their families.
    </p>
</TextContainer>

